    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="595"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d595">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> papers, <persName>Whitman</persName>
                    file</note>
                <note n="1" xml:id="d595fn1">A copy of this memorandum is also in file
                    795.00/6–1453.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                            State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-14">June 14,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Korean Situation</item>
                </list>
                <p>I attach hereto: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Copy of my personal message to President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName> of June 12 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>]<note n="2"
                                xml:id="d595fn2">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1165">p.
                                1165</ref>.</note> (previously sent you).</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Telegram from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BEO1"
                            >Briggs</persName>, reporting on the reception of this message.<note
                                n="3" xml:id="d595fn3">Dated June 12, <ref target="#pg_1166">p.
                                    1166</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Personal telegram from <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>,
                            suggesting I come to Korea.<note n="4" xml:id="d595fn4">
                                <hi rend="italic">
                                    <ref target="#d595">Supra</ref>
                                </hi>.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The importance of getting <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> to accept
                    the armistice can hardly be overestimated. Also, it is important to provide him
                    some “face-saving” formula. It is possible that my acceptance of <persName
                        corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s invitation, coupled with specific
                    assurances given him in Korea with reference to a security pact and coordinated
                    action in the political conference, could serve this purpose.</p>
                <p>However, on balance, I feel that it would be a mistake for me as Secretary of
                    State to go there before <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s position
                    on the armistice has been made clear and when he has not answered your letter. I
                    do think, <pb facs="0051" n="1169" xml:id="pg_1169"/> however, that it might
                    serve a useful purpose if someone of high but lesser position such as <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWS1">Robertson</persName> or <persName corresp="#p_MDII1"
                        >MacArthur</persName> should go there for the purpose of explaining and
                    developing with <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> the reality of the
                    post-armistice proposals which you made in relation to (<hi rend="italic"
                    >a</hi>) security pact, (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) economic assistance and (<hi
                        rend="italic">c</hi>) a political program for Korean unity. He should
                    preferably go prior to the Bermuda Conference, as <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> will surely be suspicious that at Bermuda we will be
                    persuaded by <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName> into a course of
                    action lenient toward Communist China.</p>
                <p>I believe that in this way we might get <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                        >Rhee</persName> thinking more about post-armistice conditions and what
                    these could mean for him, and that in the meanwhile he might allow the armistice
                    to become an accomplished fact.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">John Foster Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
